{
  "texts": [
    "In this approach, a random forest (RF) binary classifier [39] is trained to predict whether a given N-body particle -i.e.",
    "the matter contained in a voxel in the initial conditions -will end up in a halo above a specified mass threshold at redshift z = 0.",
    "The input features are derived from the density trajectory δ(R), evaluated at the Lagrangian position of the particle.",
    "The model performs comparably to standard collapse-based approaches, and interestingly, adding tidal field descriptors such as ellipticity and prolateness does not yield a significant gain in accuracy [38].",
    "The RF classifier has also been shown to outperform other binary classification algorithms [40] and remains effective even in modified gravity scenarios with a fifth force [41]."
  ]
}